TPP scores.  Difference in perceived susceptibility (i.e., the third person perception, or TPP scores) will be obtained by subtracting the participants’ own rating of the argument’s convincingness from their expectations of how convincing each of the “other” groups of people would find the argument (e.g., TPP = Other Group – Self Rating). Therefore, TPP scores could range from +100 (indicating that the participant thinks the “other” would be completely convinced whereas the participant is not at all convinced) to -100 (indicating that the participant is completely convinced and thinks that the other would not be convinced at all) for each of the eight different “other” groups (e.g., TPP_Rural = Rating for people who live in rural areas – rating for the self; TPP_Biblit = Rating for people who believe the Bible should be interpreted literally – rating for the self). Participants were asked about each of the following identity groups: Republicans, Democrats, biblical literalists, atheists, rural dwellers, urban dwellers, people who didn’t go to college, and people who attended graduate school. Thus, there will be a TPP score for each of the different “other” groups.

Conspiracy mentality will be measured using the 5-item generalized conspiracy mentality scale by Bruder and colleagues (2013). Participants will be shown each statement, such as “many important things happen in the world, which the public is never informed about”, and asked whether the statement is (1) definitely false, (2) probably false, (3) probably true, or (4) definitely true. The scale will be analyzed using item response theory and cronbach’s alpha and combined into an averaged index.

Call for Censorship. We will ask participants about censoring flat Earth videos on YouTube. For these items, participants will be shown a series of statements and asked to what extent they agreed or disagreed with those statements (strongly disagree = 1 to strongly agree = 6). The statements include asking participants whether YouTube should:
•	shut down or delete channels that upload flat Earth videos; 
•	ban users who upload flat Earth videos; 
•	delete videos that argue the Earth is;
•	demonetize channels that upload flat Earth videos; 
•	refrain from recommending flat Earth videos to other users; and 
•	be fined for distributing flat Earth videos. 
As for our second study preregistration, we stated we will create an averaged index using these items so long as the items have good inter-item reliability (Cronbach’s alpha &gt; .80) and a scree “acceleration factor” test shows evidence for one factor. It is worth noting in our second study, however, that the non-graphical solutions (e.g., parallel analysis, optimal coordinates analysis) suggest a two-factor solution. We may see this for this survey as well. If this is the case, we will report an analysis using the two-factor solution in an appendix. 

Religiosity. Participants will be asked two questions to gauge their religiosity: (1) how much guidance does your faith, religion, or spirituality provide in your day-to-day life on a 6-point scale (not religious to a great deal) and (2) do you pray, and if so, how often, on a 5-point scale (I don’t pray to at least daily). These two items will be centered and scaled before being averaged together and rescaled.

